there are outliers in amount and balance columns, which maximum is 8835.98 and 267128.52 respectively.¶

Initially I used the IQR method as outlier detection and replace the outliers with maximum of upper limitation and lower limitation, however, this was not an optimal solution. Then I used the 1st and 99th percentiles method which gives me more control over the data.¶

Checking the correlation between the features using heatmap¶

In [36]:

months={8:'August',9:'September',10:'October'}
df['trans_month']=df['trans_month'].map(months)

df['trans_time'] = df['trans_time'].astype('int')
In [38]:
# visualize correlation of the following columns 
df_corr = df[['amount','age','balance','card_present_flag','trans_month','trans_time','trans_day']]
In [39]:
# heatmap: we can see age and balance have a strong positive correlation
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (8, 5)
sns.heatmap(df_corr.corr(),annot=True,vmax=0.3,linewidths=0.5)
plt.savefig('figure/heatmap.png')

in terms of positive Correlation which we can consider -¶

    1. The age and balance have the strongest pos_correlation in among of features.
    1. The months of transaction and balance have high pos_correlation together.
    1. The time of transaction has a positive effect on balance.
    1. The age also has pos_correlation with amount.

in terms of negtive Correlation -¶

    1. The Card_flag_present has a negative correlation with all of other features.

To analyse data we will go through time, age, gender and location¶

1 . age perspective¶

We used age to divide the data into six classes, 18 - 28, 29 - 38, 39 - 48, 49 - 58, 59 - 68, 69 - 78¶

from the figures, we can see -

  • The 49 - 58 age group of people has the highest amount of transactions.
  • The 39 - 48 age group was found to have the highest balance.

2 . time perspective¶

2.1 simple moving average (SMA)¶

  • Calulate the SMA of 5 days and 10 days. As we can see the SMA_5 is higher than SMA_10, so we can predict the next period of transcation would be increased.

2.2¶

  • by hours: Most of the transactions occured around 1 pm, followed by 5 pm.
  • by weekdays:
    • The highest amount transactions occured on Monday in Weekdays.
    • Saturday and Sunday have the lowest number of transactions.
  • by months:
    • Both the amount and balance in Oct are the highest among the three months.
In [45]:

4 . location perspective¶

  • It is clear that the amount of transactions happened in ACT is the highest of all other States, followed by NSW
  • In August and October ACT has the highest transactions, however NSW was first and ACT dropped to 5th place from the top.
  • Generally, Males who are from ACT and NT made the most transactions.
  • For the age range 39 - 48 we can observe that males have the highest balance in QLD and TAS, and at the same age group for females, the highest balance found in VIC.
  • Regarding the amount of transactions, the age group 49 - 58 for males from VIC and females from SA are the highest. SA's female age group of 59 - 68 seems to have very high number of transactions and occupy the seconds place, whereas for the same State, the males of the same age group ranked at a very low position. Relatively high is also the female age group of 29 - 38 females from QLD.

plt.savefig('figure/debit_credit_count_of_gender.png')
